====startt1w1====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 1 - Number Fundamentals and Place Value Introduction: Establish number concepts and place value understanding. Focus on representing whole numbers using place value concepts up to 9999 for Year 3 and up to 99999 for Year 4. Students learn to read, write and order numbers using numerals and number names. Practice counting forwards and backwards by ones, tens, hundreds and thousands from any starting point. Introduce expanded notation (e.g., 3456 = 3000 + 400 + 50 + 6). Develop understanding of the relative size of numbers through comparison activities. Use concrete materials, visual models and digital tools to represent numbers. Working mathematically through problem-solving with real-world number scenarios. Assessment focus on students' ability to confidently represent numbers in multiple ways and demonstrate understanding of place value concepts.
====endt1w1====

====startt1w2====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 2 - Place Value Consolidation and Number Patterns: Consolidate place value understanding through extended practice. Students explore patterns in the number system including skip counting by 2s, 3s, 4s, 5s, 10s, 25s, 100s, and 1000s. Identify and continue number patterns involving addition and subtraction. Use place value to round numbers to the nearest 10, 100, or 1000. Investigate the relationship between place value positions (each position is 10 times the value of the position to its right). Apply place value knowledge to solve simple problems involving large numbers. Create and describe number patterns using mathematical language. Work with number lines and hundreds charts to visualize number relationships. Reasoning activities involving explaining patterns and place value concepts to develop mathematical communication skills.
====endt1w2====

====startt1w3====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 3 - Addition Strategies and Mental Computation: Develop mental addition strategies using place value understanding. Students learn and apply various addition strategies including counting on, bridging through multiples of 10, partitioning numbers, and compensation methods. Focus on adding two and three-digit numbers mentally where appropriate. Use concrete materials and visual models to support understanding of addition algorithms. Practice vertical and horizontal addition problems. Develop fluency with addition facts to 20 and related facts for larger numbers. Explore the commutative and associative properties of addition through practical activities. Problem-solving involving addition in real-world contexts including money, measurement, and data. Encourage students to share and justify their chosen strategies, developing mathematical reasoning and communication skills.
====endt1w3====

====startt1w4====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 4 - Subtraction Strategies and Problem Solving: Develop mental subtraction strategies complementing addition learning. Students explore subtraction methods including counting back, counting up, bridging through multiples of 10, partitioning, and compensation. Focus on subtracting two and three-digit numbers using efficient mental and written strategies. Understand subtraction as the inverse of addition and use this relationship to solve problems. Practice both horizontal and vertical subtraction formats. Develop fluency with subtraction facts to 20 and apply to larger numbers. Solve multi-step problems involving both addition and subtraction operations. Use estimation to check the reasonableness of answers. Working mathematically through explaining chosen strategies and justifying solutions. Real-world problem-solving contexts including change from purchases, differences between quantities, and time calculations.
====endt1w4====

====startt1w5====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 5 - Multiplication Concepts and Skip Counting: Introduce multiplication as repeated addition and equal groups. Students develop understanding through concrete materials, arrays, and visual models. Focus on multiplication facts for 2, 3, 4, 5, and 10 times tables with emphasis on pattern recognition. Use skip counting to support multiplication learning. Create and interpret arrays to represent multiplication problems. Understand the commutative property of multiplication (3×4 = 4×3). Connect multiplication to real-world situations including groups of objects, rows and columns, and repeated addition scenarios. Practice multiplication facts through games and activities to develop fluency. Begin formal multiplication recording methods. Problem-solving involving simple multiplication situations in context. Working mathematically through reasoning about multiplication patterns and relationships.
====endt1w5====

====startt1w6====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 6 - Division Concepts and Relationship to Multiplication: Introduce division as sharing and grouping. Students explore division through concrete materials, visual models, and real-world contexts. Understand division as the inverse of multiplication and use this relationship to solve problems. Practice division facts related to learned multiplication tables (÷2, ÷3, ÷4, ÷5, ÷10). Represent division problems using arrays, sharing activities, and grouping scenarios. Develop understanding of remainder concepts in practical contexts. Use mathematical language to describe division processes (share equally, groups of, how many groups). Connect division to fractions through sharing activities. Problem-solving involving simple division situations including sharing objects equally and finding how many groups can be made. Working mathematically through explaining division strategies and connecting to multiplication knowledge.
====endt1w6====

====startt1w7====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 7 - Fraction Fundamentals and Unit Fractions: Introduce fraction concepts through concrete materials and visual representations. Students explore unit fractions (1/2, 1/3, 1/4, 1/5, 1/8, 1/10) using folding, cutting, and sharing activities. Understand fractions as equal parts of a whole and equal parts of a collection. Use fraction notation to represent equal parts. Compare unit fractions using concrete materials and visual models. Connect fractions to division (1/4 means 1 divided by 4). Identify fractions in real-world contexts including food sharing, time, and measurement. Create visual representations of fractions using circles, rectangles, and number lines. Problem-solving involving fraction concepts in practical situations. Working mathematically through reasoning about fraction size and relationships between different unit fractions.
====endt1w7====

====startt1w8====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 8 - Length Measurement and Units: Explore length measurement using informal and formal units. Students measure using body parts, classroom objects, and standard units (millimetres, centimetres, metres, kilometres). Develop understanding of the relationship between units (10mm = 1cm, 100cm = 1m, 1000m = 1km). Use measuring tools including rulers, tape measures, and trundle wheels appropriately. Estimate lengths before measuring to develop measurement sense. Compare and order objects by length. Solve problems involving measurement including perimeter of simple shapes. Record measurements using appropriate units and notation. Problem-solving involving real-world measurement contexts including distances, heights, and dimensions. Working mathematically through choosing appropriate units, estimating, and justifying measurement choices.
====endt1w8====

====startt1w9====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 9 - Time Concepts and Reading Clocks: Develop understanding of time concepts including hours, minutes, seconds, days, weeks, months, and years. Students read time on analog and digital clocks to the hour, half hour, quarter hour, and 5-minute intervals. Understand the relationship between different time units. Use calendars to explore dates, days of the week, and months of the year. Calculate elapsed time for simple intervals. Understand AM and PM notation. Connect time to daily activities and routines. Solve problems involving time calculations including duration and scheduling. Use time vocabulary accurately (before, after, earlier, later). Working mathematically through reasoning about time relationships and solving time-based problems in real-world contexts.
====endt1w9====

====startt1w10====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 1 Week 10 - Data Collection and Simple Graphs: Introduce data collection methods and simple graphing. Students collect data through surveys, observations, and experiments. Create and interpret picture graphs, column graphs, and simple bar graphs using appropriate scales. Understand the purpose of collecting and displaying data. Ask questions that can be answered through data collection. Use tally marks for data collection. Interpret information from graphs to answer questions. Compare data sets and identify patterns or trends. Problem-solving involving data analysis and making predictions based on collected information. Working mathematically through formulating questions, collecting relevant data, and drawing conclusions from graphical representations. Connect data activities to other curriculum areas and real-world contexts.
====endt1w10====

====startt2w1====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 1 - Advanced Multiplication Strategies: Extend multiplication understanding to larger numbers and additional tables. Students learn multiplication facts for 6, 7, 8, and 9 times tables using pattern recognition and relationship strategies. Develop mental multiplication methods including partitioning (distributive property) and doubling strategies. Practice vertical multiplication algorithm for two-digit by one-digit numbers. Use arrays, area models, and grid methods to support understanding. Explore multiplication patterns including multiples and factors. Problem-solving involving multiplication in measurement, money, and real-world contexts. Develop fluency through strategic practice and games. Working mathematically through explaining multiplication strategies, identifying patterns, and justifying efficient methods for different problem types.
====endt2w1====

====startt2w2====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 2 - Division with Remainders and Multi-digit Division: Extend division concepts to include remainders in practical contexts. Students solve division problems where the answer includes a remainder and interpret remainders appropriately for the context. Practice division facts for all learned multiplication tables. Begin division of two-digit numbers by one-digit numbers using concrete materials and visual models. Understand long division process through sharing and grouping activities. Connect remainders to fractions in appropriate contexts. Use estimation to check division answers. Problem-solving involving division with practical applications including sharing costs, organizing groups, and distributing resources. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate division strategies, explaining remainder interpretations, and connecting division to real-world situations.
====endt2w2====

====startt2w3====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 3 - Fraction Equivalence and Comparison: Develop understanding of equivalent fractions using concrete materials and visual models. Students explore relationships between fractions including 1/2 = 2/4 = 4/8, 1/3 = 2/6, 1/4 = 2/8. Compare fractions with the same denominator and simple fractions with different denominators. Use fraction walls, circles, and number lines to represent and compare fractions. Understand that equivalent fractions represent the same amount. Find equivalent fractions by multiplying or dividing numerator and denominator by the same number. Problem-solving involving fraction comparisons in practical contexts. Working mathematically through reasoning about fraction relationships, explaining equivalence using visual models, and justifying fraction comparisons through multiple representations.
====endt2w3====

====startt2w4====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 4 - Decimal Introduction and Place Value: Introduce decimal notation as an extension of place value system. Students explore tenths and hundredths using concrete materials, visual models, and real-world contexts. Understand the relationship between fractions and decimals (1/10 = 0.1, 1/100 = 0.01). Read and write decimal numbers to two decimal places. Use place value understanding to compare and order decimal numbers. Connect decimals to money notation and measurement contexts. Represent decimals on number lines and using base-10 materials. Round decimals to the nearest whole number or one decimal place. Problem-solving involving decimals in practical contexts including money, measurement, and data. Working mathematically through explaining decimal place value concepts and connecting fractions to decimal representations.
====endt2w4====

====startt2w5====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 5 - Area and Perimeter Concepts: Introduce area as the amount of surface covered and perimeter as distance around. Students measure area using informal units including square tiles, grid paper, and counting methods. Calculate perimeter by measuring or adding side lengths of rectangles and simple shapes. Understand the difference between area and perimeter through practical activities. Use appropriate units for area (square centimetres, square metres) and perimeter (centimetres, metres). Explore relationship between length, width, area, and perimeter in rectangles. Design shapes with given area or perimeter constraints. Problem-solving involving area and perimeter in real-world contexts including floor coverings, fencing, and garden planning. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate measurement strategies and explaining relationships between linear and area measurements.
====endt2w5====

====startt2w6====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 6 - Mass and Capacity Measurement: Explore mass and capacity using informal and formal units. Students compare masses using balance scales and estimate masses of familiar objects. Use standard units for mass (grams, kilograms) and capacity (millilitres, litres). Understand relationships between units (1000g = 1kg, 1000mL = 1L). Measure capacity using measuring cups, jugs, and containers. Solve problems involving mass and capacity including cooking, shopping, and scientific contexts. Choose appropriate units for different measurement situations. Use measuring instruments accurately and record measurements appropriately. Problem-solving involving mass and capacity calculations including finding differences, totals, and conversions between units. Working mathematically through estimating measurements, selecting appropriate tools and units, and explaining measurement choices.
====endt2w6====

====startt2w7====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 7 - 2D Shapes and Geometric Properties: Investigate properties of 2D shapes including triangles, quadrilaterals, pentagons, hexagons, and circles. Students identify and describe shape properties including number of sides, vertices, angles, and lines of symmetry. Classify triangles and quadrilaterals based on their properties. Understand angle concepts including right angles, acute angles, and obtuse angles. Create shapes using various materials and tools. Identify shapes in the environment and architecture. Explore tessellations and patterns using 2D shapes. Understand symmetry concepts including lines of symmetry and rotational symmetry. Problem-solving involving shape identification, classification, and property analysis. Working mathematically through describing geometric properties using appropriate mathematical language and reasoning about shape relationships.
====endt2w7====

====startt2w8====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 8 - 3D Objects and Spatial Relationships: Explore properties of 3D objects including prisms, pyramids, cylinders, cones, and spheres. Students identify and describe properties including faces, edges, vertices, and curved surfaces. Understand nets of 3D objects and construct simple objects from nets. Investigate relationship between 2D faces and 3D objects. Use appropriate mathematical language to describe 3D objects and their properties. Create 3D objects using various construction materials. Identify 3D objects in the environment and everyday life. Explore cross-sections of 3D objects. Problem-solving involving 3D object identification, construction, and property analysis. Working mathematically through spatial reasoning, explaining 3D object properties, and making connections between 2D and 3D geometry concepts.
====endt2w8====

====startt2w9====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 9 - Location and Direction: Develop understanding of position and movement using maps, grids, and coordinate systems. Students describe location using directional language (north, south, east, west, left, right, forwards, backwards). Use simple coordinate systems and grid references to locate objects and positions. Create and interpret simple maps and plans. Understand scale in mapping contexts. Give and follow directions for movement and navigation. Use compass directions and landmarks for location description. Explore transformation concepts including slides, flips, and turns. Problem-solving involving navigation, mapping, and spatial reasoning. Working mathematically through describing location and movement precisely, interpreting spatial information, and creating accurate spatial representations.
====endt2w9====

====startt2w10====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 2 Week 10 - Probability and Chance: Introduce probability concepts through practical activities and games. Students explore chance events and use language including impossible, unlikely, equally likely, likely, and certain. Conduct simple probability experiments including coin tosses, dice rolls, and spinner activities. Record and analyze results of chance experiments. Understand that some events are more likely than others. Predict outcomes and compare predictions with actual results. Create simple probability experiments and games. Use fractions to express simple probabilities. Problem-solving involving chance and probability in everyday contexts including weather, games, and decision-making. Working mathematically through predicting outcomes, conducting experiments systematically, and reasoning about probability concepts using appropriate mathematical language.
====endt2w10====

====startt3w1====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 1 - Mental Computation Strategies Review: Consolidate and extend mental computation strategies for all four operations. Students select and apply efficient mental methods for addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. Review and practice number facts to develop fluency and automaticity. Use estimation strategies to check reasonableness of calculations. Apply mental computation in real-world problem-solving contexts. Explore patterns in number facts and use these to extend learning. Compare different mental strategies and discuss efficiency for various problem types. Use calculators appropriately to support learning and check calculations. Problem-solving involving multi-step calculations using mental strategies. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate strategies, justifying mathematical thinking, and explaining computational choices for different problem contexts.
====endt3w1====

====startt3w2====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 2 - Written Algorithms and Formal Methods: Develop proficiency with formal written algorithms for addition, subtraction, and multiplication. Students practice vertical algorithms with regrouping (carrying and borrowing). Understand the mathematical reasoning behind algorithm steps. Use written methods when mental computation is not efficient. Check calculations using inverse operations and estimation. Compare written methods with mental strategies to select appropriate approaches. Apply written algorithms to solve complex multi-step problems. Use appropriate mathematical recording and layout. Problem-solving involving calculations requiring formal written methods including financial calculations, measurement conversions, and data analysis. Working mathematically through explaining algorithm steps, justifying method selection, and connecting formal procedures to conceptual understanding.
====endt3w2====

====startt3w3====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 3 - Fraction Operations and Mixed Numbers: Extend fraction understanding to include addition and subtraction of fractions with the same denominator. Students explore improper fractions and mixed numbers using concrete materials and visual models. Convert between improper fractions and mixed numbers. Add and subtract fractions with same denominators in practical contexts. Understand relationship between whole numbers, fractions, and mixed numbers. Use number lines to represent and operate with fractions. Solve problems involving fractions in measurement, cooking, and sharing contexts. Compare and order mixed numbers and improper fractions. Working mathematically through explaining fraction operations, justifying conversion methods, and connecting fraction concepts to real-world applications requiring fractional thinking.
====endt3w3====

====startt3w4====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 4 - Decimal Operations and Applications: Develop skills in adding and subtracting decimal numbers using concrete materials, visual models, and written algorithms. Students align decimal points correctly in written calculations. Understand place value in decimal operations. Use decimals in money calculations including adding costs, calculating change, and finding totals. Apply decimal operations to measurement contexts including length, mass, and capacity. Round decimal answers appropriately for context. Use estimation to check decimal calculations. Solve multi-step problems involving decimal operations. Connect decimal operations to fraction understanding. Working mathematically through explaining decimal calculation methods, selecting appropriate precision for answers, and applying decimal concepts in practical problem-solving situations.
====endt3w4====

====startt3w5====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 5 - Measurement Conversions and Problem Solving: Practice converting between different units within the same measurement attribute. Students convert between millimetres and centimetres, centimetres and metres, grams and kilograms, millilitres and litres. Understand multiplicative relationships between units. Choose appropriate units for different measurement situations. Solve complex measurement problems involving multiple steps and unit conversions. Use measurement in practical contexts including construction, cooking, and scientific investigations. Calculate with mixed units and express answers in appropriate forms. Apply measurement concepts to calculate area, perimeter, and volume of simple shapes. Working mathematically through selecting efficient conversion strategies, justifying unit choices, and solving authentic measurement problems requiring mathematical reasoning.
====endt3w5====

====startt3w6====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 6 - Advanced Time Calculations: Extend time concepts to include complex calculations involving hours, minutes, and seconds. Students calculate elapsed time across different time periods including hours and days. Use 24-hour time notation and convert between 12-hour and 24-hour formats. Solve problems involving time zones and international time differences. Calculate with time units including adding and subtracting time intervals. Use calendars for complex date calculations including finding dates before and after given periods. Apply time concepts to timetables, schedules, and planning activities. Understand concepts of duration, speed, and timing. Working mathematically through solving complex time problems, explaining time relationships, and applying temporal reasoning to real-world scheduling and planning situations.
====endt3w6====

====startt3w7====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 7 - Geometric Transformations and Symmetry: Explore transformations including translations (slides), reflections (flips), and rotations (turns) using concrete materials and coordinate grids. Students identify and create symmetric patterns and designs. Use mirrors and tracing to investigate reflection symmetry. Understand rotational symmetry in shapes and patterns. Apply transformations to create tessellations and artistic patterns. Describe transformations using appropriate mathematical language. Identify transformations in art, architecture, and natural patterns. Combine transformations to create complex designs. Problem-solving involving geometric transformations in design and spatial reasoning contexts. Working mathematically through describing transformations precisely, predicting transformation results, and explaining geometric relationships in symmetric and transformed figures.
====endt3w7====

====startt3w8====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 8 - Angles and Geometric Reasoning: Develop understanding of angle concepts including right angles, acute angles, obtuse angles, and straight angles. Students measure angles using informal methods and begin using protractors. Identify angles in 2D shapes and 3D objects. Understand that angles are measures of turn or rotation. Create and classify angles using various materials and tools. Explore angle relationships including angles on straight lines and around points. Apply angle knowledge to analyze and create geometric designs. Understand perpendicular and parallel line relationships. Working mathematically through describing angle properties, reasoning about angle relationships, and applying geometric knowledge to solve problems involving angle measurement and geometric construction.
====endt3w8====

====startt3w9====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 9 - Advanced Data Analysis and Statistics: Extend data analysis skills to include more complex graphs and statistical concepts. Students create and interpret line graphs, stem-and-leaf plots, and dot plots. Calculate and interpret measures of central tendency including mode, median, and mean. Compare data sets using statistical measures and graphical representations. Conduct statistical investigations involving data collection, organization, analysis, and interpretation. Use technology tools for data analysis and graph creation. Identify trends, patterns, and outliers in data sets. Make predictions and inferences based on data analysis. Working mathematically through formulating statistical questions, selecting appropriate data display methods, and drawing evidence-based conclusions from statistical investigations.
====endt3w9====

====startt3w10====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 3 Week 10 - Financial Mathematics and Consumer Applications: Apply mathematical skills to financial contexts including budgeting, saving, and consumer decisions. Students calculate profits, losses, and discounts in business contexts. Understand percentage concepts as parts per hundred and apply to financial calculations. Compare prices, calculate best buys, and analyze value for money. Use spreadsheets and calculators for financial calculations. Explore compound interest concepts and long-term financial planning. Apply mathematical reasoning to consumer problems including loan calculations and investment decisions. Understand concepts of income, expenses, profit, and loss. Working mathematically through analyzing financial situations, making informed consumer decisions based on mathematical analysis, and explaining financial calculations and reasoning.
====endt3w10====

====startt4w1====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 1 - Integration and Review of Number Concepts: Synthesize learning from previous terms focusing on number and algebra concepts. Students demonstrate mastery of place value, number operations, and mental computation strategies across all four operations. Apply number skills to complex, multi-step problem-solving situations. Review and consolidate multiplication and division facts for all tables to 12. Practice efficient mental and written calculation methods. Use number concepts in cross-curricular contexts including science, geography, and social studies. Explore patterns and relationships in number systems. Problem-solving involving real-world applications requiring sophisticated number reasoning. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate computational methods, explaining mathematical thinking, and demonstrating fluency with number concepts and operations.
====endt4w1====

====startt4w2====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 2 - Advanced Fraction and Decimal Applications: Apply fraction and decimal knowledge to complex problem-solving situations. Students work with mixed numbers, improper fractions, and decimal equivalents in practical contexts. Convert between fractions, decimals, and percentages for simple cases. Use fractions and decimals in measurement, data analysis, and financial mathematics. Compare and order fractions and decimals using multiple strategies. Apply fraction and decimal operations to multi-step problems. Understand fraction and decimal concepts in scaling and proportion problems. Connect fraction and decimal learning to algebraic thinking. Working mathematically through reasoning about fractional and decimal relationships, selecting appropriate representations, and applying fractional thinking to authentic problem-solving contexts.
====endt4w2====

====startt4w3====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 3 - Comprehensive Measurement Applications: Integrate all measurement concepts including length, area, volume, mass, capacity, and time in complex problem-solving contexts. Students solve multi-step measurement problems requiring unit conversions and calculations. Apply measurement concepts to design and construction projects. Use measurement in scientific investigations and data collection. Calculate composite areas and volumes of combined shapes. Apply scale factors in maps, models, and plans. Use measurement concepts in financial contexts including materials costing and project budgeting. Problem-solving involving measurement estimation, precision, and error analysis. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate measurement strategies, justifying measurement choices, and explaining measurement relationships in practical applications.
====endt4w3====

====startt4w4====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 4 - Geometric Problem Solving and Spatial Reasoning: Apply geometric knowledge to complex spatial reasoning and design problems. Students analyze and create geometric patterns, tessellations, and artistic designs. Use coordinate geometry to describe location and movement. Apply transformation geometry to practical design problems. Investigate geometric properties through construction and analysis activities. Use geometric concepts in architecture, art, and engineering contexts. Solve problems involving geometric measurement including area, perimeter, and angles. Apply geometric reasoning to navigation and mapping problems. Working mathematically through visualizing spatial relationships, explaining geometric reasoning, and connecting geometric concepts to real-world design and construction applications.
====endt4w4====

====startt4w5====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 5 - Advanced Statistics and Probability: Conduct comprehensive statistical investigations involving data collection, analysis, and interpretation. Students use statistical reasoning to make predictions and informed decisions. Apply probability concepts to games, simulations, and real-world events. Compare theoretical and experimental probability through extensive trials. Use technology tools for statistical analysis and probability simulations. Create and interpret complex graphs and statistical displays. Apply statistical concepts to scientific investigations and social studies contexts. Understand bias, sampling, and variability in data collection. Working mathematically through formulating statistical questions, designing appropriate investigations, and drawing evidence-based conclusions from statistical analysis.
====endt4w5====

====startt4w6====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 6 - Mathematical Modeling and Real-World Applications: Apply mathematical skills to model and solve authentic real-world problems. Students work on extended projects requiring multiple mathematical concepts and skills. Use mathematical modeling to investigate environmental, social, and economic issues. Apply mathematics to STEM contexts including engineering design challenges and scientific investigations. Use technology tools for mathematical modeling and analysis. Communicate mathematical findings through reports, presentations, and displays. Collaborate on mathematical investigations and problem-solving projects. Connect mathematics learning to career applications and future study. Working mathematically through formulating problems mathematically, selecting appropriate mathematical tools and strategies, and presenting mathematical arguments and conclusions.
====endt4w6====

====startt4w7====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 7 - Problem Solving Strategies and Mathematical Thinking: Develop and apply systematic problem-solving strategies including working backwards, making tables, drawing diagrams, and looking for patterns. Students analyze problem-solving approaches and evaluate solution strategies. Apply mathematical reasoning to non-routine and open-ended problems. Use multiple representations to explore and solve problems. Develop persistence and resilience in mathematical problem solving. Share and critique problem-solving approaches with peers. Apply creative thinking to mathematical investigations. Connect problem-solving strategies across different mathematical contexts. Working mathematically through analyzing problem structures, selecting appropriate strategies, and reflecting on mathematical thinking processes to improve problem-solving effectiveness.
====endt4w7====

====startt4w8====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 8 - Mathematical Communication and Justification: Focus on communicating mathematical thinking clearly and precisely using appropriate mathematical language, symbols, and representations. Students explain mathematical reasoning verbally and in writing. Justify solutions and approaches using mathematical evidence. Critique mathematical arguments and identify errors in reasoning. Use mathematical vocabulary accurately and appropriately. Create mathematical explanations for different audiences. Present mathematical findings through various formats including written reports, oral presentations, and visual displays. Engage in mathematical discourse and debate. Working mathematically through articulating mathematical thinking, constructing logical arguments, and evaluating mathematical reasoning to develop sophisticated mathematical communication skills.
====endt4w8====

====startt4w9====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 9 - Technology Integration and Digital Mathematical Tools: Explore and apply digital tools for mathematical learning including calculators, spreadsheets, graphing software, and mathematical apps. Students use technology appropriately to support mathematical investigation and problem solving. Create digital mathematical presentations and reports. Use online resources for mathematical research and exploration. Apply technology tools for data analysis, graphical representation, and mathematical modeling. Understand appropriate and inappropriate uses of technology in mathematics. Explore coding and programming concepts through mathematical contexts. Develop digital citizenship skills in mathematical contexts. Working mathematically through selecting appropriate digital tools, evaluating technological solutions, and integrating technology effectively with mathematical thinking and learning.
====endt4w9====

====startt4w10====
Year 3-4 Mathematics Term 4 Week 10 - Synthesis, Assessment, and Future Learning: Synthesize and demonstrate learning from the entire year through comprehensive assessment tasks and reflection activities. Students complete portfolio assessments showcasing mathematical growth and achievement. Reflect on mathematical learning journey and identify areas for future development. Apply integrated mathematical knowledge to complex, authentic assessment tasks. Demonstrate mathematical proficiency across all strands through varied assessment formats. Set goals for continued mathematical learning and development. Celebrate mathematical achievements and growth throughout the year. Connect current learning to future mathematical study and applications. Working mathematically through demonstrating mathematical competence, reflecting on learning processes, and articulating mathematical understanding across all areas of the curriculum.
====endt4w10====